Phishing attacks often exploit user impulsivity, leading to reflexive clicks on malicious links without proper evaluation. While prior research has explored phishing awareness, there remains a gap in understanding impulsive clicking behavior. In this study, we present a novel approach to characterize clicking impulsivity using browser history data. Our session-level analysis reveals that user's impulsive clicking behavior is situational and context dependent. Our findings offer actionable insights for adaptive security interventions based on real-time user behavior.